<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="407" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1540,2033]" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,499,1719,1744]" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">Distribution and habitat.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[507,686,1719,1744]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Varzea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="6" pageNumber="407" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bistriata">
<emphasis box="[507,686,1719,1744]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">Varzea bistriata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is endemic to Amazonia, distributed along the Amazon River and some of its main tributaries, especially the western ones (Negro, Japurá, Juruá, Purus and Madeira), and the lower part of the eastern ones (
<collectingRegion box="[430,543,1791,1816]" country="Brazil" name="Tocantins" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">Tocantins</collectingRegion>
, Xingu and Trombetas); it reaches the coastal area in 
<collectingCountry box="[1154,1222,1791,1816]" name="Brazil" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion box="[1238,1321,1792,1816]" country="Brazil" name="Amapa" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">Amapá</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[1377,1428,1792,1816]" country="Brazil" name="Para" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">Pará</collectingRegion>
) and 
<collectingCountry box="[200,370,1828,1853]" name="French Guiana" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">
<collectingRegion box="[200,370,1828,1853]" country="France" name="Guyane" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">French Guiana</collectingRegion>
</collectingCountry>
, and apparently is rare or absent at the upper and middle 
<collectingRegion box="[1026,1137,1828,1853]" country="Brazil" name="Tocantins" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">Tocantins</collectingRegion>
, Xingu and Tapajós rivers (
<figureCitation box="[159,227,1863,1888]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1128,1150]" captionTargetBox="[154,1434,203,1101]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,195,1107]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 3. Distribution of examined material of Varzea altamazonica and V. bistriata." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/197980/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). It occurs in 
<collectingCountry box="[381,452,1863,1888]" name="Brazil" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[463,632,1863,1888]" name="French Guiana" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">
<collectingRegion box="[463,632,1863,1888]" country="France" name="Guyane" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">French Guiana</collectingRegion>
</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[642,755,1863,1888]" name="Colombia" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[767,818,1864,1887]" name="Peru" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">Peru</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[872,955,1863,1888]" name="Bolivia" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[970,1037,1863,1888]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1128,1150]" captionTargetBox="[154,1434,203,1101]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,195,1107]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 3. Distribution of examined material of Varzea altamazonica and V. bistriata." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/197980/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
), and in 
<collectingCountry box="[1135,1203,1863,1888]" name="Brazil" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">Brazil</collectingCountry>
it is known from the states of 
<collectingRegion box="[252,336,1900,1924]" country="Brazil" name="Amapa" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">Amapá</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[349,402,1900,1924]" country="Brazil" name="Para" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">Pará</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[414,530,1900,1925]" country="Brazil" name="Maranhao" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">Maranhão</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[542,660,1900,1924]" country="Peru" name="Amazonas" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">Amazonas</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[717,817,1900,1925]" country="Brazil" name="Roraima" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">Roraima</collectingRegion>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[828,1008,1900,1925]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Varzea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="6" pageNumber="407" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bistriata">
<emphasis box="[828,1008,1900,1925]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="407">Varzea bistriata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is semi-arboreal and diurnal, inhabits 
<taxonomicName box="[151,224,1936,1959]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Varzea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="6" pageNumber="426" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">varzea</taxonomicName>
(periodically flooded) forest, where it is found on the ground, on low vegetation and on fallen trunks, usually in or close to sunny spots; found also in some perianthropic environments in Manaus, Belém and Breves municipalities (
<bibRefCitation author="Avila-Pires" box="[324,520,2008,2033]" pageId="6" pageNumber="407" refString="Avila-Pires, T. C. S. (1995) Lizards of Brazilian Amazonia (Reptilia: Squamata). Zoologische Verhandelingen, 299, 1 - 706." type="journal article" year="1995">Ávila-Pires 1995</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
